{
  "doc_id": "34233",
  "text": "Melanomas can contain tens of thousands of mutations [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . While metastases can be genetically divergent from primary tumors [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , heterogeneous BRAF mutation status has also been demonstrated between individual circulating melanoma cells [CITATION_5] . In primary and metastatic lesions, Takata et al. [CITATION_6] demonstrated different clonal heterogeneity using microsatellite markers mapping to chromosomes 6q, 9p, 10q and 18q to assess LOH. Recently, a heterogeneously present NRAS mutation was reported in a progressing lesion following treatment with vemurafenib [CITATION_7] . However, there has been no genome wide characterization of genetic heterogeneity within metastatic melanoma lesions to date. Likewise it is unknown whether cell lines retain genetic heterogeneity representative of the original tumor.",
